## Invariants

- New runtime schema must update `001_schema.sql`; do not rely only on an
  incremental migration for fresh installs.
- Migration filenames must use the next unused numeric prefix; avoid duplicate
  prefixes because files sort lexically.
- Column removal or data reshaping belongs in an incremental migration with
  guarded reads/writes.
- Auth secrets stay in auth tables, not `users`.
- `001_schema.sql` contains the current inbox-participant and provisioning
  baseline before `002_seed.sql`; migrations 018 and 029 remain guarded bridges
  for older deployments.
- Normalized custom-page tables use `page_section_instances` and
  `page_section_instance_items`; the dormant global `page_sections`/`page_items`
  names are not repurposed.
- Migration 030 creates storage only. Existing page rows are projected through
  the bounded `page-section-shadow-backfill` command so schema SQL never parses
  heterogeneous or sensitive page content.
- Migration 031 changes only the page-scoped theme-token order uniqueness timing;
  the 0-63 bounds and final uniqueness still apply at transaction commit.
- Migration 032 preserves Q&A moderation fields and respondent identity after a
  user-row deletion, scopes idempotency uniqueness to the stable respondent key,
  and adds content-free page response-migration readiness. Sensitive document
  parsing remains in the bounded resumable Go backfill, not schema SQL.
- Migration 033 stores only cutover counts, timestamps, statuses, and mismatch
  codes. Removing `pages.content` writes is not part of schema migration: the
  operational preflight must first prove every page ready, a complete quiet
  release window, empty dormant legacy tables, and an explicit external-job
  dependency review.

## Verify

- `find backend/internal/migrations -maxdepth 1 -type f -name '*.sql' | sort`
- `rg "CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS|ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS|ON CONFLICT" backend/internal/migrations`

